text: you're listening to the sound of
Beethoven's Fur Elise and so are a pair
of Bionic ears the bionic ear hears
differently than we do it picks up
electromagnetic signals in the same
frequency range as humans but it also
picks up much higher frequencies that we
can't hear it could greatly extend the
range of human hearing graduate student
Manu manure an engineering professor
Michael McAlpin of Princeton University
led the team that made the Bionic years
to make the Bionic years they start out
with a computer-generated drawing of
what they want to make they load inks
containing cells silicon and silver
nanoparticles into a 3d printer and use
them to print the ear layer by layer to
test the ears hearing they expose it to
electromagnetic signals from a
transmitting loop antenna a coil
receiver on one side of the ear picks up
the signal the receiver is connected to
a helical wire on the other side that
wire is shaped like the cochlea in a
normal ear they collect the output from
the wire with electrodes connected to a
digital oscilloscope and a pair of
loudspeakers that music you hear is
actually the output from the Bionic ears
converted into a form that we can hear
in the future manure and McAlpin hope to
use other materials to make Bionic ears
that can pick up sound waves as well as
electromagnetic radiation I'm Celia
Arnaud reporting for chemical and
engineering news
